ess ornate, box containing information relating to the scribeBinding: Ottoman (?) binding in red leather with blind-tolled borders, medallion and pendants; no envelope flapCondition: light waterstains, some foxing, and a notable amount bleed-through of black inkMarginalia: Frequent marginalia by more than one handSeals: See ff. 1r, 2r, 3r, 170r</extent></physicalDescription><abstract>The medical formulary of Am&#299;n al-Dawlah Ab&#363; al-&#7716;asan Hibat All&#257;h ibn &#7778;a&#8216;&#299;d known as Ibn al-Tilm&#299;dh (d. 560 AH/AD 1165), chief physician at the &#8216;A&#7693;ud&#299; Hospital in Baghdad, and later court physician to the Abbasid Caliph al-Muqtaf&#299; (reg. 1136-1160). This copy was completed some 63 years after the author&#8217;s death, in 625 AH/AD 1227-28 by &#8216;Al&#299; ibn Ab&#299; &#7788;&#257;lib ibn &#8216;Al&#299; ibn &#8216;Al&#299; ibn &#8216;Al&#299; ibn al-&#7716;usayn al-&#7716;alab&#299;, probably at Baghdad (see title page f. 2v, lines 6-9, transcribed below).The text is divided into 20 chapters (&#1571;&#1576;&#1608;&#1575;&#1576;; see table of contents on ff. 2v-3r):&#1575;&#1604;&#1576;&#1575;&#1576; &#1575;&#1604;&#1571;&#1608;&#1604; &#1601;&#1610; &#1575;&#1604;&#1571;&#1602;&#1585;&#1575;&#1589; (&#8216;Chapter 1: Pastilles&#8217;; ff. 3v-18v);&#1575;&#1604;&#1576;&#1575;&#1576; &#1575;&#1604;&#1579;&#1575;&#1606;&#1610; &#1601;&#1610; &#1581;&#1576;&#1608;&#1576; &#1608;&#1575;&#1604;&#1573;&#1610;&#1575;&#1585;&#1580;&#1575;&#1578; (&#8216;Chapter 2: Pills and electuaries [&#299;y&#257;rj&#257;t]&#8217;; ff. 19r-27v);&#1575;&#1604;&#1576;&#1575;&#1576; &#1575;&#1604;&#1579;&#1575;&#1604;&#1579; &#1601;&#1610; &#1587;&#1601;&#1608;&#1601;&#1575;&#1578; (&#8216;Chapter 3: Powders&#8217;; ff. 28r-35r);&#1575;&#1604;&#1576;&#1575;&#1576; &#1575;&#1604;&#1585;&#1575;&#1576;&#1593; &#1601;&#1610; &#1605;&#1593;&#1575;&#1580;&#1610;&#1606; (&#8216;Chapter 4: Pastes&#8217;; ff. 35r-41v defective at end);&#1575;&#1604;&#1576;